value.0: You gaze at the Witch's Tarot the Night Hag gave you. It depicts a stern-jawed figure reaching for a golden chalice with bloodied hands. A vision comes to you...
You see yourself travelling with a fool who once betrayed you but who no longer recognizes your own face. Your journey together will be long and he will not know you until the very last...
You try to see more but the vision fades. All you can cling to is the image of that golden chalice, far away.
You gaze at the Witch's Tarot the Night Hag gave you. It depicts a figure reaching for a golden chalice. Friends and compatriots lift the figure within its reach. A vision comes to you...
You see yourself meeting an old friend with whom you have journeyed many leagues. As the two of you swap tales, meat roasts on a spit nearby. He urges you to help yourself for it is in good supply...
You try to see more but the vision fades. All you can cling to is the image of a golden chalice, high above you.
You gaze at the Witch's Tarot the Night Hag gave you. It depicts a figure sitting beneath a golden chalice, holding the moon and sun between two hands. A vision comes to you...

You see yourself, lost and alone, imprisoned with someone no more fortunate than yourself. The darkness of the place is oppressive and rats scurry about your feet. Their meat is tough and tasteless...
You try to see more but the vision fades. All you can cling to is the darkness that surrounds the moon and sun.
You gaze at the Warlock's Tarot the Night Hag gave you. It depicts a white-robed figure, shafts of light lending their upturned face a holy radiance. Suddenly you remember...
You made a righteous pact that day. You and all the others with you. A great evil had been unleashed and you would be its hunter. The evil had drawn first blood but you swore to draw the last...
You struggle to remember more but the only image that fills your mind is that of the roiling smoke above you being pierced by holy light.
You gaze at the Warlock's Tarot the Night Hag gave you. It depicts a black-robed figure kneeling beside a frozen corpse. Snow falls upon the icy scene. Suddenly you remember...
It was ash, not snow, and the corpse was that of a woman. She had high cheekbones and golden hair held back by a jeweled tiara. The night was warm but frost clung to her eyes and lips...
You struggle to remember more but the only image that fills your mind is that of your teardrops freezing as they touched her face.
You gaze at the Warlock's Tarot the Night Hag gave you. It depicts a man and woman, their naked limbs entwined with satin sheets, a long shadow being cast over them. Suddenly you remember...
It was you who cast the shadow; you, the bearer of bad tidings. It was to have been a night of revelry. A night of drink and dancing. The long war was finally over and the feasting had just begun...
You struggle to remember more but the only image that fills your mind is that of your shadow casting its pall upon that night.
You gaze at the Warlock's Tarot the Night Hag gave you. The painted scene depicts someone with wild eyes holding up a feeble lantern amidst a heavy storm. Suddenly you remember...
The storm had been above you, the rains forming a raging torrent through the sewers where you hid. There was a murderer there with you, somewhere in the wettened dark. Your torch was running out...
You struggle to remember more but the only image that fills your mind is that of a face looming from the shadows.
You gaze at the Warlock's Tarot the Night Hag gave you. The painted scene depicts a savage brute beneath an ash-gray sky, their blade held high and wreathed in blood. Suddenly you remember...
There was blood on the warm stone floor and sounds of battle echoing through the castle halls. Someone had been killed and you were chasing the murderer, intent on vengeance...
You struggle to remember something more but the only image that fills your mind is that of an ash-gray sky.
These dried leaves of the deadly nightshade plant have been carefully wrapped by the Night Hag from whom you bought them. Ingesting them in this quantity will result in a quick but painless death.
The taste is bittersweet. In seconds, you can feel a numbness spreading through your body. You close your eyes... and slip... away...
A message, still in its original Elven, has been diligently copied onto this scrap of paper.
<StartAction>[Failure]</Start> You rack your brain, trying to decipher the Elven text but to no avail.
<StartAction>[Success]</Start> You manage work out a translation on the reverse of the page: "If the Cavanaugh Stone gave birth to Brogan's Tears, then to find the mother I must pursue the child."
You read the message in your mother tongue: "If the Cavanaugh Stone gave birth to Brogan's Tears, then to find the mother I must pursue the child." You scribble a quick translation onto the reverse.
A message, still in its original Elven, has been diligently copied onto this scrap of paper. Try as you might, however, you can't make any sense of it. You'll have to find a translator.
The rusted helmet is ill-fitting, with a few uncomfortable dents. The visor is lifted, rusted into position.
This rusty helm comes with an equally rusted visor. The metal screeches against itself as you try to lift and close it.
You don the helmet. It's ill-fitting, with a few uncomfortable dents.

The metal gives a tortured screech as you force the visor down. Suddenly it slams shut with heavy clang. You open your eyes to find yourself gazing through the grill into a different place, a different time.
You're standing atop some temple dais in a wooded glade, crossbow in hand. A chasm drops away to your right, spanned ahead of you by a lengthy bridge where a battle rages.
Demons, wreathed in flame, fight their way across the bridge, carving their way through an army of dwarves. You let a quarrel fly.
A fireball explodes at the temple's base and a devilish howl rises from the chasm below. The dwarf beside you panics, throwing his jammed crossbow into the yawning abyss.

A massive creature claws its way up from the rift but the dwarf is already gone. You can hear a stone slab sliding into place behind you and the sound of the panicked dwarf setting a trap upon the door.

Free of the rift, the horrendous creature rises into the air. You let another quarrel fly but it is too late. The monster breathes and your world is engulfed in flame. With a scraping sound, the visor lifts.
As you gaze upon this finely crafted pike, you are overwhelmed by the memory of Prince Ahmed's broken body suspended upon it. Your heart fills with despair and your mind with dark thoughts.
<StartAction>[Will Save: Failure]</Start> You cannot bring yourself to do it. Weeping, you turn away.
<StartAction>[Will Save: Success]</Start> Steeling your mind against the grizzly task, you drive the pike into your chest.
There is a shock of pain as you feel the spear's broad head pass between your ribs. Slowly, everything fades to black around you.
Your memories of this place are still too fresh. Haunted by the image of your Prince's face, you cannot bring yourself to do it. Weeping, you turn away.
The ring seems cold and thin upon your finger. Dark figures dance chaotically around the iron band.
You listen closely for any hint of the rings former whisper but can hear nothing on the winds. It seems to be gone, at least for now.
You hear a whisper, distant and torn by unseen winds, as you gaze upon the ring.
You gaze at the strange iron ring, holding it up to the light. Chaotic figures dance endlessly along its edge.
You slide the ring onto your finger, the metal cold and unforgiving. You hear nothing this time. The whisper seems to be gone, at least for now.
You slide the ring onto your finger, the metal cold and unforgiving. You hear a whisper as you do so, distant and torn by unseen winds.
The whisper grows closer and closer until it seems to be all around you. "<FullName>," it breathes, "it is good to return to you. You have done the Prince a great honor."
"You listened to him," confides the whisper. "You listened to his heart. The others, they listened only to their own. You obeyed his wishes and obey them still. Do not forget that."
The whisper passes through you playfully, resonating within your bones. "The Prince is dead. Long live the Prince."
There is the sound of playful laughter, fading on the wind. "The Prince is dead. Long live the Prince," the voice whispers again, as if the meaning is somehow self-evident.
The whisper swirls around you, speaking first in one ear, then the next. A breeze stirs your hair as it passes. "Me?" the whisper asks. "I am just someone to whom you have given the greatest gift."
"You gave me your trust, your loyalty and through me, you gave it to your Prince. It is the greatest gift of all to give, <FirstName>, and I thank you for it."

There is a tinkle of laughter on the winds. "I have many names. Perhaps you will remember them all someday. I would like that. For now, I am this iron ring. I'm company on a lonely road. That is enough."
Though this severed remnant of your finger has grown cold and gray, it remains strangely pliable. You're not quite sure what to do with it.
You hold the finger against its ragged, still-living stump. The finger looks dead and lifeless there, a sullen contrast to your own vitality.
The finger curls up when you pull on the tendon, extending itself again when you let go. You're surprised by how flexible it still is.
You point the finger at yourself but nothing happens. From this angle, however, you can see that dirt and dried blood has collected beneath the ragged fingernail.
